descriptions: New website created (currently accessible through the EPFL network and in its development version at https://mast-dev.epfl.ch/). The official launch of the website will be mid-August and the link have been already registered under https://masonrydb.epfl.ch
EPFL Database Overview Buildings EESD — Online platform providing data and resources on shake table tests and numerical models of masonry buildings
The new website created comprises a database of experimental results from shake table tests conducted on unreinforced masonry buildings
The website also includes a database of ready-to-use numerical models
A database of shake-table tests conducted on unreinforced masonry buildings (Version v2) [Data set]
Experimental shake table dataset for multi-storey mixed URM-RC wall - CoMa, including acceleration histories, displacement histories, crack maps, and related test data
OpenSees numerical model files (Tcl scripts, .vtk file, scheme.png) for the multi-storey mixed URM-RC wall - CoMa

Equivalent frame model of masonry using OpenSees; macroelement for masonry developed by Vanin et al. (2019); detailed modeling assumptions including element types, geometry, mass, damping, and boundary conditions
A training session is expected at the SAHC conference to be held at EPFL in September 2025, where a large number of researchers from around the world focused on masonry structures will be present
Paper submitted and accepted in the Journal Earthquake Spectra under the name 'A database of shake-table tests conducted on unreinforced masonry buildings'
Manuscript (under progress) that makes use of the data provided in the platform for the quantification of uncertainties in the seismic assessment of unreinforced masonry buildings

Dynamic testing of a four-storey building with reinforced concrete and unreinforced masonry walls: prediction, test results and data set, Beyer et al. (2015), Bull. Earthq. Eng., vol. 13, no. 10, pp. 3015–3064, Oct. 2015
Presentation of the database and web-based platform at the World Conference of Earthquake Engineering (WCEE) held in Milan in July 2024
Presentation of the platform made in Colombia, Medellin. The event was organized as part of a project related to the seismic safety of rural schools in Colombia
Activity organized within the EESD lab for testing the platform

This number is based on statistics collected from the Zenodo repository at https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.11093882, given the total amount of views and downloads of the database already made. The community being benefited is mainly the research community working on unreinforced masonry buildings.
